Jo G
New Zealand54 contributions
Great place - opportunity lost
Dec 2022 • Family
This place was well worth a visit. We went with a local guide and it was worth it because he showed us a lot that standard tours don’t see. The temples are beautiful and the caves truely amazing!
It’s a strenuous walk to the top but if you have good fitness you’ll be fine, the view of the area is nice. There is an elevator to part of the mountain.
What we could not cope with was that rubbish is left on the tracks. Surely for a tourist destination that charges an entry fee someone could send some blokes in with a rubbish bag to clear up the plastic bottles, wrappers, and everything else, that are all over the place and put some signs up that litterers will be prosecuted. It’s really not cool.
Everyone - tourists included- need to do better when it comes to rubbish. Vietnam can’t afford to lose tourists! It seems people turn a blind eye but it is absolutely putting me off this part of the world. Ban the plastics.
Written January 5, 2023
Nat C
Perth, Western Australia, Australia23 contributions
Worth the visit but be prepared to climb
Sep 2022 • Family
Beautiful pagodas and Buddha statues set among mountain forest and caves. We really enjoyed the couple of hours we spent exploring here. We took the elevator up and walked back down where there were cafes for us to grab fresh cold drinks.
Worth the visit but you’ll need to be fit and be wearing sneakers because there’s A LOT of stairs and parts that are tricky to navigate (steep climbs, narrow footholds).
It was rainy season when we visited - cloudy and 30C degrees. I couldn’t imagine doing this in the heat of Vietnamese summer!
Also, be prepared for the hard sell on marble statues and ornaments- the streets at the foot of the mountains are lined with stores selling these.
Written September 29, 2022
